It's the difference between being doing something and going online to find information or resources that you need to do that something, versus going online looking for things to do.

You can get all the things you need to build a shed by going to the hardware store, but loitering in a hardware store won't inspire you to build a shed.

The Internet has been fine tuned to make everyone loiter around advertisement impressions, waiting for those occasional interesting events that hook them, like how random rewards keep the lab pigeons pecking the red button that isn't hooked up to anything.

In the days of forums, I'd be interested in something, and commune with like minded individuals to enhance that interest. But today social media is tuned to reward people who create occasional interesting events, rewarding them with "likes" to stir their dopamine while the people pressing like convince themselves that they're being entertained.

And there is an essential difference.
People will plan three hours to watch a football game.
People will plan three hours to see a rock concert.
Nobody plans to spend three hours scrolling imgur or shitposting X. It just happens. Because it's a psychological trick, not a product. (inb4 you're the product; true but different)
Because it squeezes into the places where hobbies and activities belong, giving cheap fast dopamine by spamming material instead of helping you to choose an accomplishment and then go toward it.

And it's not all like that. There are plenty of resources still. But they're harder to find than ever, because Google doesn't get as much revenue if it helps you to build the shed as it does if it convinces you to spend three hours looking at videos of people talking about their own sheds.

NTA but nowadays there are two ways you install Arch. a) you follow the wiki guide and type out all the required commands one by one, or b) you run the archinstall script and install it with predefined settings and packages.
